<subSubSection id="C37642ECFFC6FFF2F7AD5B495365FC11" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BD31167FFC6FFF2F7AD5B495365FC11" blockId="43.[2060,2660,832,1255]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis id="B918CD75FFC6FFF2F7AD5B4952CCFCC9" bold="true" box="[2065,2221,832,861]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6C6AE4FFC6FFF2F76F5B495236FC11" authority="Wagner, 1840" authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1840" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Loncheres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obscura">Loncheres obscura Wagner, 1840</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="3B041B3AFFC6FFF2F7DB5B6D5365FC11" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3804303325" box="[2151,2308,868,901]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">“Brazilien.”</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37642ECFFC6FFF2F7B05B825D31FA99" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD31167FFC6FFF2F7B05B825D31FA99" blockId="43.[2060,2660,832,1255]" lastBlockId="43.[1450,2657,1260,2122]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">
J. A. Wagner's original description and accompanying figures suggest that this taxon 1s a 
<taxonomicName id="4C6C6AE4FFC6FFF2F71F5BEA5340FC68" authorityName="Husson" authorityYear="1978" box="[2211,2337,995,1020]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Makalata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Makalata</taxonomicName>
. It 1s unclear, however, if 
<taxonomicName id="4C6C6AE4FFC6FFF2F7935C0852ECFBB6" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[2095,2189,1025,1058]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Loncheres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obscura">obscura</taxonomicName>
is a valid species or a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6C6AE4FFC6FFF2F7AE5C2052BEFBDE" box="[2066,2271,1065,1098]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Makalata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="duidelphoides">M. duidelphoides</taxonomicName>
. Because the holotype has apparently been lost, L. H. Emmons, who in 2005 was the first to assign this taxon to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6C6AE4FFC6FFF2F7AE5C9652EEFB54" authorityName="Husson" authorityYear="1978" box="[2066,2191,1183,1216]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Makalata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Makalata</taxonomicName>
as a member of her 
<taxonomicName id="4C6C6AE4FFC6FFF2F6765C965003FB54" baseAuthorityName="Desmarest" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[2506,2658,1183,1216]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Makalata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="didelphoides">didelphoides</taxonomicName>
species group, considered Wagner’s name a nomen dubium. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37642ECFFC6FFF2FA115D1D5C05FAC8" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" type="distribution">
<caption id="DF1341EFFFC6FFF2FA115D1D5C05FAC8" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6623874" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6623874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6623874/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" startId="43.[1453,1625,1300,1333]" targetBox="[1451,2043,840,1250]" targetPageId="43">
<paragraph id="8BD31167FFC6FFF2FA115D1D5C05FAC8" blockId="43.[1450,2657,1260,2122]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis id="B918CD75FFC6FFF2FA115D1D5C3DFAA1" bold="true" box="[1453,1628,1300,1333]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">Distribution.</emphasis>
Brazil, presumably E Amazonia (Para and Maranhao states?) but not precisely known.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37642ECFFC6FFF2FA105D6A53CCF9E4" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD31167FFC6FFF2FA105D6A53CCF9E4" blockId="43.[1450,2657,1260,2122]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis id="B918CD75FFC6FFF2FA105D6A5CC7FA10" bold="true" box="[1452,1702,1379,1412]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
There are no specific measurements available. Based on two specimens collected by J. B. von Spix, G. R. Waterhouse in 1848 described the Dark Armored Tree-rat as having robust body, short feet, brown dorsum flecked with yellow, yellowish venter, thick tail about same length as head-body length and covered with very short scattered hairs, and upper body, including shoulders and thighs, with mixture of spines and scattered coarse hairs. Yellowish venter appears to align the Dark Armored Tree-rat with the Red-nosed Armored Tree-rat (
<taxonomicName id="4C6C6AE4FFC6FFF2F76D5E5A53C0F9E4" baseAuthorityName="Desmarest" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[2257,2465,1619,1648]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Makalata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="594" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="didelphoides">M. didelphoides</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37642ECFFC6FFF2FA105E7E5029F92B" pageId="43" pageNumber="595" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BD31167FFC6FFF2FA105E7E5029F92B" blockId="43.[1450,2657,1260,2122]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis id="B918CD75FFC6FFF2FA105E7E5C7AF90C" bold="true" box="[1452,1563,1655,1688]" pageId="43" pageNumber="595">Habitat.</emphasis>
There is no specific information available for this species, but the Dark Armored Tree-rat is probably an arboreal representative of lowland primary rainforest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
